{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a1f4dbc3-8688-4e75-8c89-92a8db3d1dff","content":"These are two separate issues introduced by C# 15 changes:\n\n## Issue 1: `left && right` — Dynamic `&&` binding change\n\nC# 15 changed how `&&`/`||` resolve when one operand is `dynamic`. Previously the entire expression was deferred to the runtime binder. Now the compiler **statically** resolves `operator true`/`operator false` using the compile-time type first.\n\nSince `IFilter` declares `operator true`/`operator false` but **no `operator &`**, static resolution of `&&` (which requires all three) fails.\n\n**Fixes — pick one:**\n1. Add `operator &` to the interface:\n   ```csharp\n   static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;\n   ```\n2. Force full dynamic binding by casting:\n   ```csharp\n   var combined = (dynamic)left && right;\n   ```\n\n## Issue 2: `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518\n\nCS0518 (\"Predefined type is not defined or imported\") means the compiler needs a BCL type that isn't in your referenced assemblies. C# 15 encodes `ref readonly` returns on lambdas using a new attribute type (in `System.Runtime.CompilerServices`) that your target framework may not include.\n\n**Fixes — pick one:**\n1. Ensure your SDK and runtime targeting both match .NET 11 (check `<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>` and SDK version).\n2. Use a **named local function** instead of a lambda, which doesn't need the synthesized delegate machinery:\n   ```csharp\n   static ref readonly int Fn() => ref value;\n   ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2a5f4eb3-bca8-4718-8503-32d20f9aa34e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both issues.\n\n**Issue 1: `left && right` with `IFilter left, dynamic right`**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler resolves short-circuit operators (`&&`/`||`) when one operand is `dynamic`.\n\nThe `&&` operator in C# is synthesized from `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler historically would defer resolution entirely to runtime. However, in C# 15, there's a change related to how user-defined operators interact with `dynamic`.\n\n\nThe real issue is that newer C# versions now bind `&&` and `||` at compile time when the static type provides `operator true`/`operator false` and `operator &`/`operator |`, even if the other operand is `dynamic`. Previously, the entire expression would be deferred to the runtime binder, but now the compiler tries to resolve it statically first. tries to resolve interface operators during overload resolution with dynamic operands now, whereas previously it would defer entirely to the runtime binder. For the second issue, CS0518 suggests a required runtime type is missing—`ref readonly` lambdas introduced in C# 12 might now require a new attribute or compiler support that isn't available in .NET 11. requires a new BCL type that the compiler can't locate, which is why we're seeing the CS0518 error. For the first issue, the problem is that C# 15 changed how `&&`/`||` operators work with `dynamic` operands—instead of deferring to runtime, it now tries compile-time binding using the static type's operators. Since `IFilter` only defines `operator true` and `operator false` but not `operator &`, the `&&` resolution fails. I need to either add `operator &` to `IFilter` or cast `left` to a concrete type.\n\nFor the second issue, the `ref readonly` return type on lambdas is a C# 15 feature that requires runtime support not present in older frameworks. I should either target .NET 11 or switch to a named method instead of a lambda. Let me reconsider the dynamic operator resolution more carefully—I'm pretty confident about the breaking change here, where older C# versions deferred everything to runtime but now the compiler attempts static resolution first. what's actually happening. For the first issue, C# 15 changed how it handles `&&` and `||` with dynamic operands—it now tries partial static binding instead of deferring everything to runtime. The compiler finds `operator true` on `IFilter` but then can't locate `operator &`, so it fails even though at runtime the actual `CompositeFilter` instance would have that operator. The second issue is that `ref readonly` return lambdas are a new C# 15 feature that depends on a predefined runtime type that may not be available or properly configured. The first issue looks like a breaking change in how the compiler handles dynamic binding with compound operators—it's now trying to resolve statically against `IFilter` first, which doesn't have the `&` operator defined. The second issue follows the pattern of a new language feature that requires runtime support, and CS0518 is what you get when the compiler can't find a type the runtime should provide. I should be careful here though—my training data goes through .NET 9 and C# 13, so for .NET 11 and C# 15 I'm working from patterns rather than direct knowledge, but I can still analyze what these errors are telling us about the code. types changed how they're handled. The real issue is that both of these worked before the upgrade, so they're regressions or breaking changes in the compiler or runtime between versions. the compiler now tries to statically resolve `&&` using the compile-time type instead of deferring to the runtime binder, so since `IFilter` has `operator true`/`operator false` but not `operator &`, the resolution fails—I can fix this by adding the missing operator or casting to dynamic. For the second issue, `ref readonly` return lambdas in C# 15 need a new BCL attribute type that's not present in the current SDK, so I'd need to either update the SDK or find what specific type is missing.","outputTokens":3376,"requestId":"F80D:349DAE:747AE9:8572A4:6A052B0B"},"id":"3e329ec7-7d19-457c-a092-3f2ffe1e465a","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:54:18.90